{"key":"processedPost-11111725","value":{"id":11111725,"first":11111597,"last":11115833,"when":1253723174,"utime":"09/23/09 07:26 PM","cleanedPost":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />Ive used some of the myc covered popcorn to inoculate many other corn jars as these seemed to colonize way faster than any of the other substrates. </blockquote><br />Popcorn is not faster than other grains.&nbsp; The mycelium only colonizes the surface, and since popcorn has such a huge surface area per grain, you have far less mycelium per jar than rye or wbs, etc. That's the reason popcorn 'appears' to colonize faster.&nbsp; It's also a poor fruiting substrate, with many species and strains refusing to fruit at all on it.&nbsp; The few that will fruit well are the exception, rather than the rule.<br />Fresh air is the number one pinning trigger.&nbsp; You're not going to get fresh air exchange with an aquarium pump.&nbsp; I'd suggest building a <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Terrarium-Tek\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">shotgun terrarium</a>.&nbsp; Get your light on a 12/12 schedule, and use a proper LED or fluorescent light in the 6500 Kelvin color temperature range.<br />RR"}}